From fa8406e72b2d0071dc42ef275da206795e5637d3 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Yvette Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Fri, 19 Jun 2026 00:28:50 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 167/174] selinux: map the status page at MMU-page granularity
 under PGCL

sel_mmap_handle_status() rejected the mapping with -EIO unless the VMA was
exactly PAGE_SIZE.  Userspace (libselinux selinux_status_open()) maps
getpagesize() bytes, which is the MMU page size the ABI exposes to user
space -- MMUPAGE_SIZE.  Under page clustering MMUPAGE_SIZE < PAGE_SIZE, so
the check failed and every libselinux user that reads the fast status page
got EIO: dbus-broker logs "could not open selinux status page: 5 (Input/
output error)" and exits fatally, systemd restart-loops it, and the machine
never reaches a login.

The status struct lives at the head of the page and remap_pfn_range()
already maps per-MMUPAGE from the cluster pfn, so gating on MMUPAGE_SIZE and
mapping that many bytes is sufficient.  MMUPAGE_SIZE == PAGE_SIZE when
PAGE_MMUSHIFT == 0, so non-clustered builds are unchanged.

Found on a Fedora laptop (SELinux enforcing) booting PAGE_MMUSHIFT=4: the
kernel was otherwise clean (full userspace + systemd) but blocked here.
Matrix-invisible -- the QEMU test rootfs runs no SELinux.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01UkhHXA2PvPb3uwymHGbYh8
---
 security/selinux/selinuxfs.c | 12 ++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/security/selinux/selinuxfs.c b/security/selinux/selinuxfs.c
index 25ca7d714014..06cc48468695 100644
--- a/security/selinux/selinuxfs.c
+++ b/security/selinux/selinuxfs.c
@@ -246,8 +246,16 @@ static int sel_mmap_handle_status(struct file *filp,
 
 	BUG_ON(!status);
 
-	/* only allows one page from the head */
-	if (vma->vm_pgoff > 0 || size != PAGE_SIZE)
+	/*
+	 * Only allows one page from the head.  Userspace (libselinux
+	 * selinux_status_open()) maps getpagesize() bytes, i.e. one MMU page
+	 * (MMUPAGE_SIZE), which under page clustering is smaller than the
+	 * kernel PAGE_SIZE.  Gate on MMUPAGE_SIZE so the status struct (which
+	 * lives at the head of the page) can be mapped; remap_pfn_range() below
+	 * maps the first MMU page of the cluster.  MMUPAGE_SIZE == PAGE_SIZE
+	 * when PAGE_MMUSHIFT == 0, so non-clustered behaviour is unchanged.
+	 */
+	if (vma->vm_pgoff > 0 || size != MMUPAGE_SIZE)
 		return -EIO;
 	/* disallow writable mapping */
 	if (vma->vm_flags & VM_WRITE)
